post_text:
On June 3, 2020, Warren County hosted a virtual Battle of the Books Competition for grades 3 and 4.

We had two teams:

Franklin Red: Charlie Roberto, Danny Opie, Brayden Morgan, and Ava Scorsone. Franklin Red got 123 pts, which earned them Gold level certificates,

Franklin Black: Braden Young, Cadence McGinnis, Sean Hadzic, and Mia Brown. Franklin Black got 110 pts, which earned them Silver level certificates

Both teams were outstanding! Everyone contributed, and scored big.

Both teams "won" their respective competitions, beating long standing Warren County Winners!

Congratulations to both teams and Mrs. Wester and Mrs. Weinstein for sponsoring.

post_text: Franklin School was very well represented for the New Jersey PTA Reflections Program. Students from around the New Jersey submitted entries in the categories of Dance, Literature, Music Composition, Visual Arts, Photography, and Film Production. Franklin School took home 3 first place finishes for Warren County: Rowan Pehrson – Photography, Charles Roberto – Literature, Amelia Roberto – Literature. 2 second place finishes: David Fitzsimmons – Literature, Matteo Raggazo – Visual Arts. 2 third place finishes: Sean Hadzic – Literature, Ayden Klemer – Photography. We also had two students place at the State Level. Those students were: Amelia Roberto – Literature, Sean Hadzic – Literature. Thank you to all students who participate and their teachers for guiding them along. Go Fireballs!

post_text: STEAM Night at Franklin Township School!!! The STEAM initiative at Franklin School was developed collaboratively through professional development and cross-curricular development. STEAM represents the integration of science, technology, engineering, art and mathematics. The underlying goal is to help students internalize a process for solving problems utilizing critical thinking skills. This educational approach is multi-dimensional and encourages experiential learning, student inquiry, collaboration and creativity. The STEAM movement has gained traction as a positive response to the complex needs of a 21st century economy.

Mr. Lucante was the captain of a New York Waterway ferry that responded to and assisted passengers off the plane of the "Miracle on the Hudson" event with Captain Sullenberger on January 15, 2009. Mr. Lucante shared his career path and the events of that cold January day with Mrs. Brown's first grade class and Mrs. Dillon's PreSchool Class. Thanks for visiting Mr. Lucante!!!

post_text: During the Second Marking period, students in the 6th grade were busy studying Ancient Egypt. Students were assigned a project consisting of constructing a 3 dimensional model of Khufu’s Burial Pyramid, The Great Sphinx, or developing a poster and digital presentation to share the information they learned. With a cross-curriculum assignment with their Visual Art class, students designed portraits of themselves as Pharaohs’. What an AMAZING job they have done!

post_text: In Second Grade the students read the story "Pearl and Wagner; Two Good Friends", where two friends worked together to build their own robot. The Second Grade students were asked to design their own robot at home. They had to come up with a plan and share what materials they would be using. They then had to build it and write a story about what it is able to do. Here is the final product!

post_text: Kindness Starts with you - As part of our Kick Off to Kindness Week, "Rocket" from the Harlem Wizards came to Franklin to talk to our kids about Kindness and promote a Project Graduation Event for Warren Hills High School. Staff and students participated in this highly entertaining and motivational presentation. The Harlem Wizards will be at Warren Hills High School on Friday, November 30 (right after the Franklin Tree Lighting Ceremony). Proceeds will support Project Graduation for the class of 2019 at Warren Hills. "Remember, no act of kindness, no matter how small, is ever wasted." - Aesop

post_text: Every year, PTA sponsors a contest (Reflections - this year's theme was "Within Reach") for students in the categories of Literature, Visual Arts, Music Composition, Film and Photography. I am proud to announce that Franklin had 10 winners this year! The awards were announced at the Warren County PTA Founders' Day Dinner last night at Architects Club in Lopatcong. Congratulations to all students that participated in this opportunity!

post_text: Congratulations to Mrs. Fellner in her receipt of the First Energy STEM Grant sponsored by JCP&L in the amount of $665. Mrs. Fellner used the grant money to purchase 20 magnetic levitation train kits to teach students about harnessing the power of magnetism. Students and the JCP&L representatives gathered around to preview a sample of the train kit and how technology will integrate into their investigations.
